        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-06-16T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-06-16T14:00:00-05:00" n="1274"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1274">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72112/2611</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PWH1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-06-16T14:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 16, 1916, 2 p. m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3430. Your despatch 3317, March 23,<note n="1" xml:id="d1274fn1">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_945">p. 945</ref>.</note> and
                    Department’s instruction 3681, June 2.<note n="2" xml:id="d1274fn2">See footnote
                        4 to Mr. <persName corresp="#p_TWH1">Taft</persName>’s latter of May 8,
                        1916, <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_947">p.
                        947</ref>.</note> Red Cross suggests as a possible solution to the
                    differences which now exist, in its view of the obligation of British Government
                    under the Geneva convention and its announced policy in limiting the permits for
                    shipments of medical supplies to the Red Cross hospital units in the territory
                    of the Central powers, that, while American Red Cross has no further funds with
                    which to maintain medical or hospital units in territory Central powers, it
                    would be able to send to Central powers a commission of satisfactory persons to
                    receive Red Cross shipments, superintend their distribution to hospitals, and
                    supervise their use, commission to be composed of persons for whose good faith
                    Red Cross would vouch in seeing that supplies were devoted to hospital purposes
                    only and to relief of sick and wounded. Red Cross would be glad to submit names
                    of persons constituting such commission to British Government before appointing
                    them, and expresses hope that British Government will agree to this proposition.
                    Present this proposal to British Government and urge prompt reply.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
